    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a7d1b7a8-1236-4099-b5a8-2c6c48757f37",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old Czech woman with a medium build and slightly hunched posture, presenting to an outpatient rehabilitation clinic in Brno with a 6-month history of persistent low back pain radiating intermittently into her left buttock and thigh, consistent with sciatica [SNOMED:M54.5]. She describes the pain as a dull, aching sensation that worsens after prolonged sitting at her desk and is accompanied by marked tenderness on palpation of the lumbar paraspinal musculature [SNOMED:M54.5]. She visibly winces when rising from the examination chair and walks cautiously. She also reports significant anxiety about her ability to continue working, which she attributes partly to the chronic nature of her pain [SNOMED:M54.5].\n\n{patientName} works as an administrative accountant at a mid-sized company in Brno, spending the majority of her 8-hour workday seated in front of a computer. She lives with her husband in a flat on the third floor of a building without a lift, which she finds increasingly challenging to climb. Her two adult children live independently. She enjoys reading, knitting, and occasional walks in the Moravian countryside on weekends, although the latter have become infrequent due to her back complaints.\n\nShe describes her lifestyle as largely sedentary and acknowledges she has not engaged in regular exercise for several years. She is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol only socially. Her diet is typical Central European fare, moderately high in carbohydrates and fats. She has a BMI in the overweight range. She is menopausal and has not been on hormone replacement therapy.\n\n{patientName} expresses frustration that conservative treatment has provided only partial relief over the past several months [PMID:28375914]. She rates her average daily pain at 6 out of 10, which significantly limits her functional capacity and contributes to poor sleep and mood disturbance [PMID:16154380]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:76953b1f-8f39-4cfc-83da-1c5ce3dd8600",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior history of malignancy, making a malignant aetiology of her low back pain less likely; however, red flags were formally assessed and ruled out [PMID:28375914, PMID:34503841]. She has been managed conservatively for approximately 6 months with partial response [PMID:28375914]. She has a history of mild gastro-oesophageal symptoms for which she takes a proton pump inhibitor, relevant given her NSAID use.\n\nShe has no prior hospitalizations related to her back and no previous surgical interventions on the spine. She underwent a lumbar epidural steroid injection 2 years ago for a prior episode of acute radiculopathy, which provided temporary relief [PMID:28375914]. She has also undergone supervised physical therapy of the lumbar spine on two separate occasions [PMID:16154380].\n\nShe has a sedentary occupational lifestyle and BMI in the overweight range, both recognised risk factors for CLBP [PMID:16154380]. She is post-menopausal and not on HRT. She reports no bowel or bladder dysfunction. She has no known history of inflammatory arthritis or spondyloarthropathy. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol only occasionally."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
